# Show the total number of visits for each year by region
overseas_residents_uk_visits_annual <- overseas_residents_uk_visits %>% 
  group_by(year, region) %>% 
  summarise("total_number_of_visits_thousands" = sum(number_of_visits_thousands))
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
overseas_residents_uk_visits_annual %>% 
  filter(region != "all_visit") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = year, 
             y = total_number_of_visits_thousands, 
             fill = region)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(title = "Annual UK Visits by Region",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Number of Visits (Thousands)")

Here we can see the spread of regions people tavel to the UK from. The UK recieved approximately 40 million visitors from overseas in 2018 and showed a slight increase in 2019. However we can see a sharp decrease in 2020/ 20201 due to the covid pandemic there has been a significant increase in overseas visitor numbers reaching just over 30 million however the UK is yet to return to pre pandemic levels. The majority of overseas visits are from Europe.
